transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Viagra, I can help you today. Yeah, my name is Robert Jasper and I just received ten—

Speaker 2: Viagra pills in the mail. I didn't order none.

Speaker 1: Yeah, most likely it's based on your prescription from your original order. What's your last name and a zip code?

Speaker 2: Last name is Jasper, J-A-S-P-E-R, 8-5-3-5-1, and I've always ordered as I needed. I never was set up on a program.

Speaker 1: No, there's always going to be a set refill date for the prescription because that's the only way it remains active, sir. Without that, the whole profile itself will be closed out. I did pull you up here right now and I do see your last order was done on December 22nd.

Speaker 2: Whenever that order was done, it triggered it back again to every month. It looks like you were set up to—

Speaker 1: every three at first.

Speaker 2: They never did. I've been buying them from you for a long time and I've never ever, I call and I, when I want them, I call.

Speaker 1: Last time you called was in June of 2025, sir, since then things have changed. That's why I'm trying to get you the new one.

Speaker 2: No, no, I didn't call in June. I called probably, you know, earlier, like—

Speaker 1: December. I have the logs here, sir. Your last call up to us was done on June 3rd, 2025.

Speaker 2: No, no, I had one way—

Speaker 1: later.

Speaker 2: Look, I had one way later than that because I only got nine left. I only got—

Speaker 1: nine left. I'm trying to look on my computer here.

Speaker 2: No, I understand, but we're seeing this here too, sir. That's what I'm trying to explain to you.

Speaker 1: Well, don't, I don't want them. I'll send them back.

Speaker 2: That's not a—

Speaker 1: problem. Instead of arguing, why didn't you just request that from the start?

Speaker 2: I did.

Speaker 1: Very good. You said that you never signed up for a refill system, so you didn't mention that.

Speaker 2: No, I never did. I never did. I called back and I said, look, I want them as I need them, and then I'll order as I need it.

Speaker 1: Okay, well, you can send them back for a refund, sir, but what I'm trying to say is we don't offer that type of service, so you need to have a refill date to keep it active.

Speaker 2: I know, I got, look, what date did you—

Speaker 1: I'm looking on the last charge you got on, Mike. Maybe if you just for one second only talk, because you were talking quite a lot right now, I could probably get some information to you, but if you keep talking, I don't think I'm going to be able to give you any information.

Speaker 2: Well, I've never had problems like this with anybody before. Usually I talk to a lady.

Speaker 1: Yeah, I like what I'm saying, sir. I want to know what's taking—

Speaker 2: your charge, what date were they charged out on? So if you just let me tell you that date, I can tell you that, but you just keep talking, sir.

Speaker 1: All right, take a look.

Speaker 2: So yeah, like I was already trying to tell you, it was done on January 22nd. You could send it back for the refund. Once it gets to our pharmacy, they'll give you a refund.

Speaker 1: I want to talk to somebody else.

Speaker 2: January 22nd, I'm looking here.

Speaker 1: Yeah, January 22nd.

Speaker 2: Okay, I got it right here. $63.95. Look, I've been buying these—

Speaker 1: for years, not weeks, months, years. I don't know what the heck's going on here.

Speaker 2: Well, like I just explained to you, sir, the rules have changed. You need to have a refill date—

Speaker 1: to have the prescription.

Speaker 2: I didn't change nothing.

Speaker 1: Okay, so I'm listening well enough, sir, because—

Speaker 2: I didn't say you changed anything. You listened to me for a minute.

Speaker 1: No, sir, because you just—

Speaker 2: didn't seem to understand.

Speaker 1: I keep trying to tell you that you didn't change anything.

Speaker 2: I said the rules have changed on our things regarding the prescriptions.

Speaker 1: I got to talk—

Speaker 2: to somebody else.

Speaker 1: Yeah, look.
